/*
 * WEEK 3 - LOOPS & NUMBER THEORY
 * Topic: Operator Precedence and Associativity
 * File: 8.Precedence_Associativity
 *
 * CONCEPT:
 * Operator precedence determines which operator is evaluated first in an
 * expression with multiple operators. Associativity determines the order
 * of evaluation when operators have the SAME precedence level.
 *
 * KEY POINTS / ALGORITHM:
 * 1. Higher precedence operators are evaluated before lower ones.
 *    Example: 10 + 20 * 30 = 10 + (20 * 30), NOT (10 + 20) * 30.
 * 2. Associativity is only used when two or more operators share the same precedence.
 * 3. Left-to-right associativity: +, -, *, / (most binary operators).
 * 4. Right-to-left associativity: =, +=, unary operators.
 * 5. Associativity does NOT define operand evaluation order for a single operator.
 * 6. All operators with the same precedence have the same associativity.
 * 7. Java does NOT support chaining comparison operators (a > b > c is invalid).
 * 8. Best practice: use parentheses to make intent explicit and avoid confusion.
 *
 * Time Complexity: N/A (conceptual topic, not an algorithm)
 * Space Complexity: N/A
 */


/*
 * KEY RULE 1: Precedence determines evaluation order for different operators.
 * Example: 10 + 20 * 30 is calculated as 10 + (20 * 30) and not as (10 + 20) * 30.
 */


/*
 * KEY RULE 2: Associativity is only used when there are two or more operators
 * of the same precedence in an expression.
 *
 * NOTE: Associativity does NOT define the order in which operands of a single
 * operator are evaluated. For example, in F1() + F2(), even though + is
 * left-to-right associative, it does NOT guarantee F1() is called before F2().
 * The output of the following program is actually compiler-dependent.
 */

// Example: Associativity does not determine operand evaluation order
static int x = 0;
  public static int F1() {
      x = 5;                            // modifies shared variable x
      return x;
    }
  public static int F2() {
      x = 10;                           // also modifies shared variable x
      return x;
     }

public static void main(String[] args) {
      int p = F1() + F2();              // order of F1()/F2() evaluation is not guaranteed
      System.out.println(x);            // result depends on which function runs last
    }


/*
 * KEY RULE 3: All operators with the same precedence have the same associativity.
 * This is necessary; otherwise, the compiler could not resolve expressions with
 * two operators of the same precedence but different associativity.
 * Example: + and - both have left-to-right associativity.
 */


/*
 * KEY RULE 4: There is no chaining of comparison operators in Java.
 * Writing a > b > c will cause a compilation error.
 * Instead, use: (a > b) && (b > c)
 */


